's Philosophy-Screens follows Deleuze's call for "a philosophy-cinema" that can account for these fundamental changes in perception and aesthetic production, and adapts it to twenty-first-century concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny20th century. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Aesthetics. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Metaphysics. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Aesthetics.2bisacsh1 aNijhuis, Marta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143847466340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438474663423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438474663/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles